00:58:58,220 --> 00:59:00,868
carry it back over the
fence, put it in their car.

1185
00:59:00,869 --> 00:59:04,305
<i>When they drive from
Wyoming to South Dakota,</i>

1186
00:59:04,306 --> 00:59:06,306
<i>they then have conducted</i>

1187
00:59:06,307 --> 00:59:08,642
<i>an illegal act which is called</i>

1188
00:59:08,643 --> 00:59:10,944
<i>interstate transportation
of stolen property.</i>

1189
00:59:10,945 --> 00:59:12,577
<i>They get back to the Institute.</i>

1190
00:59:13,014 --> 00:59:14,816
<i>They would make a phone call,</i>

1191
00:59:14,817 --> 00:59:16,718
<i>send a fax, maybe, to Japan,</i>

1192
00:59:16,719 --> 00:59:19,087
<i>and say, "We found the thing
that you were looking for."</i>

1193
00:59:19,088 --> 00:59:20,988
Do you want to buy it?"

1194
00:59:20,989 --> 00:59:23,091
Well, that's wire fraud.

1195
00:59:23,092 --> 00:59:25,759
<i>And then if the Japanese museum</i>

1196
00:59:25,760 --> 00:59:27,895
<i>were to purchase that fossil</i>

1197
00:59:27,896 --> 00:59:29,832
and the guys would put
that money in the bank,

1198
00:59:30,032 --> 00:59:31,633
that's money laundering.

1199
00:59:31,634 --> 00:59:34,968
So basically the guys
were called conspirators

1200
00:59:34,969 --> 00:59:39,806
who were creating
this very elaborate scheme

1201
00:59:39,807 --> 00:59:41,676
to intentionally steal things

1202
00:59:41,677 --> 00:59:42,941
and sell them illegally.

1203
00:59:59,827 --> 01:00:01,235
<i>As the months went by,</i>

1204
01:00:01,262 --> 01:00:05,066
things seemed to get darker
and darker and darker.

1205
01:00:05,067 --> 01:00:06,734
For quite a while, we'd hoped

1206
01:00:06,735 --> 01:00:08,335
that they'll gain their senses

1207
01:00:08,336 --> 01:00:09,937
and this'll just go away.

1208
01:00:09,938 --> 01:00:13,306
Because it was so hotly
contested along the way,

1209
01:00:13,307 --> 01:00:16,276
I didn't think there
would be any chance

1210
01:00:16,277 --> 01:00:18,212
that this case would
settle before trial.

1211
01:00:18,213 --> 01:00:21,149
By late summer of '94,

1212
01:00:21,150 --> 01:00:22,850
there were serious discussions

1213
01:00:22,851 --> 01:00:24,819
that were going on with the U.S.
Attorney's office

1214
01:00:25,019 --> 01:00:26,421
for a possible resolution.

1215
01:00:26,422 --> 01:00:28,355
I go out on my step one morning

1216
01:00:28,356 --> 01:00:29,825
and bring the "Rapid
City Journal" in

1217
01:00:30,025 --> 01:00:32,359
and have a cup of coffee,
and right on the front page

1218
01:00:32,360 --> 01:00:34,364
<i>is the plea agreement announced.</i>

1219
01:00:36,364 --> 01:00:39,232
<i>Somebody spilled their guts</i>

1220
01:00:39,233 --> 01:00:40,968
<i>in front of Hugh O'Gara,</i>

1221
01:00:40,969 --> 01:00:43,303
and he might as well have
taken a gun and shot us.

1222
01:00:43,304 --> 01:00:44,971
<i>The article itself</i>

1223
01:00:44,972 --> 01:00:47,107
<i>suggested capitulation</i>

1224
01:00:47,108 --> 01:00:48,709
<i>on the part of the government.</i>

1225
01:00:48,710 --> 01:00:50,310
You never get a good deal done

1226
01:00:50,311 --> 01:00:52,145
if somebody is going to be cast

1227
01:00:52,146 --> 01:00:54,781
as having folded their tent.

1228
01:00:54,782 --> 01:00:57,417
<i>Anybody who would publish
that should know better,</i>

1229
01:00:57,418 --> 01:00:58,986
<i>so I called Hugh O'Gara,</i>

1230
01:00:58,987 --> 01:01:01,189
<i>and I just said,
"What were you thinking?</i>

1231
01:01:01,190 --> 01:01:03,124
How could you do that?"

1232
01:01:03,125 --> 01:01:04,991
And he was near tears
on the phone.

1233
01:01:04,992 --> 01:01:06,393
He would not answer me.

1234
01:01:06,394 --> 01:01:07,995
Hugh would never...

1235
01:01:07,996 --> 01:01:10,098
obviously would not tell
me who that source was.

1236
01:01:10,099 --> 01:01:11,198
I wouldn't even ask him.

1237
01:01:11,199 --> 01:01:12,199
<i>The next morning,</i>

1238
01:01:13,001 --> 01:01:16,104
<i>the judge called all the
attorneys into chambers.</i>

1239
01:01:16,105 --> 01:01:18,939
<i>He went down the line
and made each of us</i>

1240
01:01:18,940 --> 01:01:21,942
say that we were not
responsible for the leak.

1241
01:01:21,943 --> 01:01:25,747
He felt that the principals at
least deserved to go to jail.

1242
01:01:25,748 --> 01:01:27,814
He said that he would
not accept the plea.

1243
01:01:27,815 --> 01:01:29,450
He had prejudged the case,

1244
01:01:29,451 --> 01:01:31,852
and under two federal statutes,

1245
01:01:31,853 --> 01:01:34,821
a judge is obligated
to remove themselves

1246
01:01:34,822 --> 01:01:36,758
from sitting and hearing
the rest of the case.

1247
01:01:36,759 --> 01:01:38,225
So we filed immediately

1248
01:01:38,226 --> 01:01:40,294
<i>our second recusal motion</i>

1249
01:01:40,295 --> 01:01:42,296
<i>asking the judge to step down.</i>

1250
01:01:42,297 --> 01:01:45,031
<i>The thing that seems to
upset Judge Battey the most</i>

1251
01:01:45,032 --> 01:01:47,301
<i>is not whether he's fair,</i>

1252
01:01:47,302 --> 01:01:49,403
<i>but to be challenged
that he's not being fair,</i>

1253
01:01:49,404 --> 01:01:51,299
so he immediately
denied that motion.

1254
01:02:04,085 --> 01:02:07,087
I knew this case
was going to trial

1255
01:02:07,088 --> 01:02:10,424
the day the Hugh O'Gara article

1256
01:02:10,425 --> 01:02:12,583
was published in the
"Rapid City Journal."

1257
01:02:34,182 --> 01:02:36,216
<i>I'm not afraid of 12 people,</i>

1258
01:02:36,217 --> 01:02:38,819
<i>a jury of 12 people
of our peers.</i>

1259
01:02:38,820 --> 01:02:40,988
I know that they'll
look at this case

1260
01:02:40,989 --> 01:02:43,089
and they'll see
the ridiculous way

1261
01:02:43,090 --> 01:02:44,524
in which the government
is behaving,

1262
01:02:44,525 --> 01:02:46,426
and they will vindicate us.

1263
01:02:46,427 --> 01:02:49,375
We're innocent of all the
things that we're charged with.

1264
01:03:04,045 --> 01:03:05,513
<i>So in the courtroom,</i>

1265
01:03:05,514 --> 01:03:07,415
<i>of course right in front</i>

1266
01:03:07,416 --> 01:03:09,517
<i>is Judge Battey and the bench.</i>

1267
01:03:09,518 --> 01:03:11,919
<i>Off to the left is the jury,</i>

1268
01:03:11,920 --> 01:03:13,421
<i>12 jurors, two alternates,</i>

1269
01:03:13,422 --> 01:03:16,223
<i>a large space in between
where the lawyers</i>

1270
01:03:16,224 --> 01:03:18,593
<i>get to pace and walk and
show exhibits and things,</i>

1271
01:03:18,594 --> 01:03:20,861
<i>and then we have
the prosecution,</i>

1272
01:03:20,862 --> 01:03:23,233
<i>which had at times
two or three lawyers.</i>

1273
01:03:24,833 --> 01:03:27,313
<i>On our side, there was a
lawyer for each defendant,</i>

1274
01:03:27,314 --> 01:03:30,370
<i>so there were six lawyers
and five defendants,</i>

1275
01:03:30,371 --> 01:03:31,807
<i>the sixth defendant, of course,</i>

1276
01:03:32,007 --> 01:03:34,274
<i>being the Black Hills Institute.</i>

1277
01:03:34,275 --> 01:03:35,475
<i>Our trial was...</i>

1278
01:03:35,476 --> 01:03:37,210
and still is
the largest criminal case

1279
01:03:37,211 --> 01:03:39,211
that's ever been tried
in South Dakota.

1280
01:03:42,150 --> 01:03:43,551
<i>You cannot say</i>

1281
01:03:43,552 --> 01:03:45,620
<i>the word "Sue" in the trial.</i>

1282
01:03:45,621 --> 01:03:47,221
I mean, the jurors were going,

1283
01:03:47,222 --> 01:03:48,622
"What happened to Sue?

1284
01:03:48,623 --> 01:03:50,258
That's why they got these guys

1285
01:03:50,259 --> 01:03:51,892
in the court system,
right?"

1286
01:03:51,893 --> 01:03:54,472
The logistics of this trial
were incomprehensible.

1287
01:04:01,302 --> 01:04:04,038
The Institute has collected
maybe a million fossils.

1288
01:04:04,039 --> 01:04:07,308
This indictment
covers 14 of them,

1289
01:04:07,309 --> 01:04:09,310
and those 14 fossils

1290
01:04:09,311 --> 01:04:11,345
were collected from seven sites.

1291
01:04:11,346 --> 01:04:13,446
<i>In seven cases,</i>

1292
01:04:13,447 --> 01:04:15,818
<i>in all the years these guys
have been out in the field,</i>

1293
01:04:16,018 --> 01:04:18,451
<i>they are accused of being
in the wrong place.</i>

1294
01:04:18,452 --> 01:04:20,254
<i>The government would simply</i>

1295
01:04:20,255 --> 01:04:22,089
<i>have their officials come in</i>

1296
01:04:22,090 --> 01:04:24,325
<i>of whatever agency
was going to be</i>

1297
01:04:24,326 --> 01:04:26,326
<i>taking the lead
for that particular site</i>

1298
01:04:26,327 --> 01:04:29,096
and would say, "I found where
the specimen was collected.

1299
01:04:29,097 --> 01:04:30,931
I knew, therefore,
it was on government land."

1300
01:04:30,932 --> 01:04:32,366
And to me, it just emphasized

1301
01:04:32,367 --> 01:04:35,102
the ridiculous nature
of this whole thing.

1302
01:04:35,103 --> 01:04:36,805
You know, I mean,
if it's 200 feet over

1303
01:04:37,005 --> 01:04:40,005
and you don't know where you
are, it would have been okay?

1304
01:04:43,927 --> 01:04:45,980
<i>His job had been
to appraise the fossils</i>

1305
01:04:45,981 --> 01:04:47,614
<i>that had been seized
in the case,</i>

1306
01:04:47,615 --> 01:04:51,252
<i>and his evaluations would
be incredibly important,</i>

1307
01:04:51,253 --> 01:04:53,620
because they determined
whether a given count

1308
01:04:53,621 --> 01:04:55,260
was a misdemeanor or a felony.

1309
01:04:59,260 --> 01:05:02,296
<i>It was pretty easy
in cross-examination</i>

1310
01:05:02,297 --> 01:05:04,230
to discover that the man

1311
01:05:04,231 --> 01:05:06,366
had not opened
the field jackets.

1312
01:05:06,367 --> 01:05:09,370
He was telling us
the values of things

1313
01:05:09,371 --> 01:05:10,740
he had not even looked at.

1314
01:05:33,094 --> 01:05:35,147
<i>Pete and I, on one of
our trips to Peru,</i>

1315
01:05:35,865 --> 01:05:37,497
<i>we were taking $15,000 in cash,</i>

1316
01:05:37,498 --> 01:05:39,399
<i>because down there,</i>

1317
01:05:39,400 --> 01:05:42,403
<i>you can't use credit cards
or anything else.</i>

1318
01:05:42,404 --> 01:05:45,404
<i>And he withdrew $15,000 from
the bank, and we split it up.</i>

1319
01:05:45,984 --> 01:05:47,774
Just in case
one person got robbed,

1320
01:05:47,775 --> 01:05:49,377
at least they
wouldn't lose everything.

1321
01:05:49,378 --> 01:05:51,578
Susan Hendrickson carried 8,000.

1322
01:05:51,579 --> 01:05:53,214
I carried $7,000 down

1323
01:05:53,215 --> 01:05:54,614
one of the trips of cash.

1324
01:05:54,615 --> 01:05:56,283
<i>We were building a museum,</i>

1325
01:05:56,284 --> 01:05:58,319
<i>paying for the bricks and mortar</i>

1326
01:05:58,320 --> 01:06:01,163
<i>and doing the work ourselves
with our Swiss colleagues.</i>

1327
01:06:09,030 --> 01:06:10,430
<i>In Japan, they...</i>

1328
01:06:10,431 --> 01:06:12,299
<i>the museums pay in cash.</i>

1329
01:06:12,300 --> 01:06:14,100
<i>They always have.
Didn't want to carry</i>

1330
01:06:14,101 --> 01:06:16,037
<i>bundles of cash on the
plane, so we went</i>

1331
01:06:16,038 --> 01:06:18,272
to a bank and put it
in traveler's checks.

1332
01:06:18,273 --> 01:06:19,672
They were all restrictively

1333
01:06:19,673 --> 01:06:21,174
endorsed traveler's checks,

1334
01:06:21,175 --> 01:06:22,576
all stamped for deposit only,

1335
01:06:22,577 --> 01:06:24,578
deposited in the bank.
Paid taxes on them.

1336
01:06:24,579 --> 01:06:26,413
<i>Prosecution had four
different witnesses,</i>

1337
01:06:26,414 --> 01:06:27,580
<i>all of whom testified</i>

1338
01:06:27,581 --> 01:06:29,417
<i>that restrictively endorsed</i>

1339
01:06:29,418 --> 01:06:31,258
<i>traveler's checks do not
need to be declared.</i>

1340
01:06:31,259 --> 01:06:34,120
What struck me about
the prosecution's case

1341
01:06:34,121 --> 01:06:35,790
was how complex it was.

1342
01:06:35,791 --> 01:06:38,091
People had to understand

1343
01:06:38,092 --> 01:06:41,194
<i>the arcane ins and outs</i>

1344
01:06:41,195 --> 01:06:43,430
<i>of bringing traveler's checks</i>

1345
01:06:43,431 --> 01:06:45,165
<i>into the country</i>

1346
01:06:45,166 --> 01:06:48,169
<i>and latitudes and
longitudes on public lands.</i>

1347
01:06:48,170 --> 01:06:51,171
<i>And I think they did it
in an organized way,</i>

1348
01:06:51,172 --> 01:06:53,488
but it was a very, very
complicated argument.

1349
01:06:59,213 --> 01:07:01,114
<i>When the prosecution rested,</i>

1350
01:07:01,115 --> 01:07:04,819
I felt we had put on
the evidence that we had.

1351
01:07:04,820 --> 01:07:08,154
<i>We had their own pictures of
them taking these fossils.</i>

1352
01:07:08,155 --> 01:07:11,325
<i>We had their own field notes of
them collecting these fossils.</i>

1353
01:07:11,326 --> 01:07:14,627
We had given it
100% of our effort

1354
01:07:14,628 --> 01:07:16,266
to show what they did.

1355
01:07:19,266 --> 01:07:22,736
<i>As the defense
proceeded to present</i>

1356
01:07:22,737 --> 01:07:24,205
many fewer witnesses to say,

1357
01:07:24,206 --> 01:07:25,839
"Look, it's not
that complicated.

1358
01:07:25,840 --> 01:07:27,374
We were collecting fossils.

1359
01:07:27,375 --> 01:07:29,243
We thought we had
permission to be there.

1360
01:07:29,244 --> 01:07:31,278
In this case, we weren't
where you thought we were.

1361
01:07:31,279 --> 01:07:33,385
In this case, we were.
It's that simple."

1362
01:07:37,990 --> 01:07:40,254
<i>As we were approaching
the end of the trial,</i>

1363
01:07:40,255 --> 01:07:41,589
<i>Neal and I both felt</i>

1364
01:07:41,590 --> 01:07:44,390
that it was important
for him to testify.

1365
01:07:44,391 --> 01:07:46,759
<i>3 1/2 days, I was
on the witness stand,</i>

1366
01:07:46,760 --> 01:07:48,796
<i>and for 3 1/2 days, I swore</i>

1367
01:07:48,797 --> 01:07:50,464
to tell the truth,
the whole truth,

1368
01:07:50,465 --> 01:07:52,623
and nothing but the
truth, so help me God.

1369
01:08:00,175 --> 01:08:02,142
<i>Pete ended up not testifying.</i>

1370
01:08:02,143 --> 01:08:03,776
State had not proven its case.

1371
01:08:03,777 --> 01:08:05,346
The state doesn't
prove their case,

1372
01:08:05,347 --> 01:08:08,816
your client doesn't
take the stand, period.

1373
01:08:08,817 --> 01:08:10,683
And so on the advice of counsel,

1374
01:08:10,684 --> 01:08:12,539
I did not testify.

1375
01:08:31,539 --> 01:08:33,239
<i>The jury came back today</i>

1376
01:08:33,240 --> 01:08:35,442
in the Hill City fossil hunter
federal criminal trial.

1377
01:08:35,443 --> 01:08:38,179
<i>The jury said
over and over again</i>

1378
01:08:38,180 --> 01:08:39,913
<i>either not guilty</i>

1379
01:08:39,914 --> 01:08:42,183
<i>or no unanimous verdict
could be reached.</i>

1380
01:08:42,184 --> 01:08:44,451
<i>Of over 150 charges,</i>

1381
01:08:44,452 --> 01:08:47,188
<i>the jury agreed to convict
only 13 times,</i>

1382
01:08:47,189 --> 01:08:49,723
<i>and five of those convictions
are for misdemeanor crimes.</i>

1383
01:08:49,724 --> 01:08:52,459
<i>So here is how
the convictions break down.</i>

1384
01:08:52,460 --> 01:08:55,328
<i>Pete Larson, co-owner and
founder of the Institute,</i>

1385
01:08:55,329 --> 01:08:57,363
<i>is convicted on two counts
of misdemeanor thefts</i>

1386
01:08:57,364 --> 01:08:58,732
<i>and two felony counts</i>

1387
01:08:58,733 --> 01:09:00,334
<i>of illegally transporting money</i>

1388
01:09:00,335 --> 01:09:01,669
<i>in and out of the country.</i>

1389
01:09:01,670 --> 01:09:03,670
<i>Brother Neal Larson found guilty</i>

1390
01:09:03,671 --> 01:09:05,305
<i>of one misdemeanor theft.</i>

1391
01:09:05,306 --> 01:09:06,874
<i>The jury either acquitted Neal</i>

1392
01:09:06,875 --> 01:09:09,210
<i>or couldn't agree
on a verdict for the others.</i>

1393
01:09:09,211 --> 01:09:12,212
<i>Bob Farrar, a third
co-owner of the Institute,</i>

1394
01:09:12,213 --> 01:09:13,846
<i>convicted of two felonies,</i>

1395
01:09:13,847 --> 01:09:16,750
<i>making false statements
to customs officials.</i>

1396
01:09:16,751 --> 01:09:18,919
<i>And the Black Hills
Institute as a corporation</i>

1397
01:09:18,920 --> 01:09:20,888
<i>is convicted
of two misdemeanor thefts,</i>

1398
01:09:20,889 --> 01:09:22,488
<i>a felony theft</i>

1399
01:09:22,489 --> 01:09:23,890
<i>and twice making
false statements</i>

1400
01:09:23,891 --> 01:09:25,492
<i>to customs officials.</i>

1401
01:09:25,493 --> 01:09:26,961
<i>The jury also
found the Institute</i>

1402
01:09:26,962 --> 01:09:28,895
guilty of bringing goods
in the States

1403
01:09:28,896 --> 01:09:30,598
by making a false statement.

1404
01:09:30,599 --> 01:09:32,966
Defendants Eddie Cole
and Terry Wentz

1405
01:09:32,967 --> 01:09:35,307
were not convicted
on any charges.

1406
01:09:40,247 --> 01:09:41,774
<i>As the verdict was announced,</i>

1407
01:09:41,775 --> 01:09:44,778
it was almost
impossible to believe

1408
01:09:44,779 --> 01:09:47,614
that the defense hadn't
scored a great victory.

1409
01:09:47,615 --> 01:09:50,251
However, there were

1410
01:09:50,252 --> 01:09:53,254
some fairly significant
felony convictions

1411
01:09:53,255 --> 01:09:55,922
The expression, "you could have
knocked me over with a feather"...

1412
01:09:55,923 --> 01:09:58,626
you could have knocked
me over with a feather.

1413
01:09:58,627 --> 01:10:01,495
<i>I talked to some jurors
after the trail.</i>

1414
01:10:01,496 --> 01:10:03,264
<i>Some of them were near tears</i>

1415
01:10:03,265 --> 01:10:05,633
<i>when I interviewed them
